reviewText: Following Rose was a bit of a challenge but Freema played her part well. It's not easy being the rebound companion!My Favorite, rewatchable episode is the Weeping Angels episode (oddly enough)I wish Sparrow would reappear but it would have been better if she'd done so while David Tennant was still the Dr.This wasn't my favorite season (mostly due to missing Rose) but I've come around after re-watching. I actually like Donna Best as Tennant's companion.I waited to purchase until the price was a little more reasonable to me.I swear whenever I have kids old enough I'm going to dress one in a gas mask and tell him to say, "Are you my mommy?" instead of "Trick or Treat" and the other one is going to be a Weeping Angel!  That'd be great! : DThe raggedy Dr would be fun, too.

reviewText: David Tennant, Doctor Who, a big blue box? What's not to love? I can watch these episodes again and again. The stories are interesting and fun.  You can think, or not, of a deeper meaning in most of the episodes.  I have five of the seasons, plus the David Tennant Movies, and will be buying the last two seasons soon. Martha Jones brings a real doctor to the show, and saved the doctor medically more than once, but I have to say Donna Noble was my favorite companion.

reviewText: This is my favorite season of Doctor Who.  It has Blink, my favorite Doctor Who episode, David Tennant, my favorite Doctor, and Freema Agyeman as Martha Jones, my favorite "companion" (she has spunk!).  Plus it has appearances by John Barrowman as Captain Jack Harkness (i.e. the spinoff Torchwood).  All of the episodes were very well written and the acting is superb.  The season finale, pitting the Doctor against the Master (John Simm), has an ending that is both tragic and brilliant.  If I were limited to only one Doctor Who season, this is the season that I would get.

reviewText: My first Doctor was Jon Pertwee.  I fell in love with the series way back then.  That being said, after a slight infatuation with Tom Baker, I have been deeply in love with the Tenth Doctor ever since he made his appearance.  Of all the Doctors, David Tennant is my favourite...dark, quirky, sometimes cynical, always charsmatic and sometimes brilliant.  Sigh.

reviewText: Doctor Who Series 3 continues to entertain and amaze like no other show on television. It's so nice to have the episodes uncut!  I loved this season from beginning to end. The 3 part finale had me yelling and cheering at my television numerous times. Once again, there are plenty of great special features I can not wait to check out!The only problem I have isn't with the show itself, it's the disc holders. Getting the discs out for the first time scared the hell out of me. They're rather difficult to remove, I don't know if they could actually break but I'm overly cautious. I don't know if all the sets are like this, I had the same problem with my series 2 set and I suspect series 4 will be the same. Just beware of that. I used an old CD to wear down the plastic a bit so I wouldn't live in fear of damaging these wonderful DVDs. If you love Doctor Who and can afford to buy these DVDs you won't be sorry!
summary: Another Brilliant Series Of Doctor Who
